Regression and Analysis of Variance (Dataset 1: Cancer)

B00833984 Hanwen Zhang B00763452 Wenhui Xing B00757726 Ling Jiang

12/09/2020

1. Abstract

Two possible factors GDP and Region are chosen to determine why different states have differences for being diagnosed and dying from cancer, since GDP reflects the medical resources of each state, different regions have different environments. Linear regression models are built for solving this question. The result shows the region is an essential factor to explain the difference in the death/incidence rate of different states but the GDP not. States in the south region have a larger death/incidence rate than states in the northeast, and states in north central and west have smaller values. Whats more, for incidence/death rate, when the region is fixed as north central, the state with low GDP group has the lowest value. Especially, for death rate, when the region is fixed as south, the state with a higher GDP group has the lowest incidence rate.

2. Introduction

Different states have different death rate and incidence rate of cancer. Especially, there exist some variables that have an impact on the death/incidence rate directly and then results in different death/incidence rate in different states indirectly. For example, different states may have different GDP levels, so that the medical facilities are different, which significantly influences the death/incidence rate. Whats more, each states different geographical location will also cause differences in climate, environment, etc., which will affect the incidence of cancer. In all, many factors are worthy of study to answer why different states have different death/incidence rates. In this report, I focus on two possible aspects: GDP and the region.

3. Data Description

3.1 Introduce one new additional data point into death.csv

Each row in the dataset represents a different county, and it almost contains all counties. Hence we fill in one row with the value of age_adjusted_death_rate missing instead of adding a row. The row we choose is a county with FIPS equals 2282. We have the data of its nearby county, whose FIPS is 2280. The confidence interval given in the table shows that the 95% CI of the age_adjusted_death_rate in that county is [35.3,93.3], so we choose a random value in that range to fill in the missing value of the county.

3.2 Introduce one new additional data point into incd.csv

Similarly, each row in the dataset represents a different county, and it almost contains all counties. Hence we fill in one row with the value of age_adjusted_incidence_rate_e_cases_per_100_000 missing instead of adding an additional row. The row we choose is a county with FIPS equals 56035. We have the data of its nearby county, whose FIPS is 56037. The confidence interval given in the table shows that the 95% CI of the age_adjusted_incidence_rate_e_cases_per_100_000 in that county is [30.5,51.1], so we choose a random value in that range to fill in the missing value of the county.

3.3 Merge with GDP and region data

To answer the question that we bring out in the introduction, we need to get the GDP and region data for each state and the death/incidence rate. The GDP data is also obtained from data.world. We categorize it into three groups (low, medium, high) based on the \(\frac{1}{3}\), \(\frac{2}{3}\) quantiles. We get region data directly from the package datasets in R. They divide all states into four regions: Northeast, South, North Central (Same as Midwest nowadays) and West. Detail of the data can be retrive from here.

My cleaned data for the death rate looks like below:

   region GDP_rank age_adjusted_death_rate

7    West      low                    76.2
9    West      low                    34.4
10   West      low                   124.9
12   West      low                    58.3

My cleaned data for incidence rate looks like below:

For example, in northeast, when the states level of GDP is medium, it has the lowest death rate compared to other two GDP groups. In south region, the state in the high GDP group has the lowest death rate.

3.4.6 Incidence rate for different regions and GDP groups

In north central region, the state in the low GDP group has the lowest incidence rate.

4. Methods

To select the best model, we use step forward here. The null model is only with intercept and the full model is with region, GDP_rank and their interaction term. The outcome is the death rate. This prcocess output the full model as the best model. Also, it has the smallest AIC.

4.1 Select Models for Death Rate

Start:  AIC=14861.75
age_adjusted_death_rate ~ 1

           Df Sum of Sq    RSS   AIC
+ region    3    101256 452531 14300
+ GDP_rank  2     12166 541621 14803
<none>                  553787 14862

Step:  AIC=14299.74
age_adjusted_death_rate ~ region

           Df Sum of Sq    RSS   AIC
+ GDP_rank  2     13158 439373 14221
<none>                  452531 14300

Step:  AIC=14220.74
age_adjusted_death_rate ~ region + GDP_rank

                  Df Sum of Sq    RSS   AIC
+ region:GDP_rank  6     41259 398114 13955
<none>                         439373 14221

Step:  AIC=13955.35
age_adjusted_death_rate ~ region + GDP_rank + region:GDP_rank

4.2 Select Models for Incidence Rate

The model selection for the incidence data is similar to that for the death rateThe outcome is the incidence rate, and the best model is the full model with GDP_rank, region and their interaction term.

For the result of the model for the death rate above, we can see that when the other variables are constant, the mean death rate of the South region is estimated to 12.166 more than that of the northeast. The mean death rate of the north central region is estimated to 6.105 less than that of the northeast. At the significant level of 0.05, there is no significant difference among the three GDP groups, consistent with my data visualization part statements. For the interaction term, some of them are significant. Take region south: GDP_rankhigh for example, when the region is fixed as south, the state with high GDP group is estimated to 6.850 less death rate than that of low GDP group.

The \(R^2\) is 28.1%, which implies about 28.1% variation in death rate can be explained by the model.

For the result of the model for the incidence rate above, we can see that when the other variables are constant, the South regions mean incidence rate is estimated to 7.85 more than that of the northeast. The mean incidence rate of north central region is estimated to 11.972 less than that of the northeast. For the interaction term, some of them are significant. Take regionNorth Central: GDP_rankhigh and regionNorth Central: GDP_rankmedium. The \(R^2\) is 27.5%, which implies about 27.5% variation in indience rate can be explained by the model.

6. Conclusion

  • Region: States in the south region has a higher death/incidence rate than states in the northeast when other variables are constant. States in north central and west have lower death/incidence rates.

  • GDP groups: There is no significant evidence that shows that the death/incidence rate is different among the three GDP groups. However, this should be important, according to our common sense. In the future, we might try to use different indicators to denote each states economic status or even the indicator of the invest of medical facilities to explore more.

  • Interaction terms: For incidence rate, when the region is fixed as north central, the state with low GDP group has the lowest incidence rate. For death rate, same as the incidence rate, when the region is fixed as north central, the state with low GDP group has the lowest death rate. Furthermore, when the region is fixed as south, the state with high GDP group has the lowest incidence rate.
